<section class="fabrik-section">
  <div class="fabrik-container">
    <div class="fabrik-narrative">
      <header data-part="header">
        <span data-part="eyebrow">Why Fabrik</span>
        <h2 data-part="title">Why we built Fabrik.</h2>
      </header>

      <div data-part="beat">
        <h3>The world we built for</h3>
        <p>
          The tools most teams reach for to build, test, and run their code
          grew up around one particular user: a human developer at a terminal,
          running a command a few dozen times a day, skimming the output, and
          forming a mental model of the project from what scrolls past. Every
          choice these tools make is calibrated for that user. Verbose logs.
          Approximate errors. Implicit toolchains. Ergonomics tuned for one
          language at a time.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div data-part="beat">
        <h3>What changed</h3>
        <p>
          The shape of the work has shifted. Coding agents now sit alongside
          humans in the same repo. They iterate faster, run many attempts in
          parallel, and unlike humans, they cannot skim. A two-gigabyte log is
          not signal to an agent; it is a wall. They need the system that
          runs their work to talk back in structures they can query, not
          paragraphs they have to parse.
        </p>
        <p>
          The economics shift too. One developer running their build, test,
          and dev commands forty times a day is comfortable on a local cache.
          The same developer with two agents working alongside is not. Cache
          hit rates that felt fine for one person collapse the moment several
          attempts share most of their inputs but each re-run from scratch.
          Shared, content-addressed caching and the ability to offload work
          to remote runners stop being optimizations and become the price of
          doing the work at all.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div data-part="beat">
        <h3>Where the seams show</h3>
        <p>
          Today's tools were not built with this in mind, and the seams show.
          Diagnostics are written for a human reader, not a machine consumer.
          The dependency graph is implicit, locked inside the tool's head,
          instead of something you can ask questions of. Reproducibility is
          best-effort, which is fine when you trust your own laptop and
          uncomfortable when an agent claims a run passed on a machine you
          cannot see. Per-language tools fragment exactly when cross-language
          pull requests are getting more common, not less.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div data-part="beat">
        <h3>What Fabrik does differently</h3>
        <p>
          Fabrik is an automation kernel. It sits between humans, coding
          agents, and the execution infrastructure beneath them: local cache,
          remote runners, and the toolchains they invoke. Every action is
          content-addressed, with a declared input digest and a deterministic
          environment, so a cache hit on your laptop, in CI, and on a remote
          runner all mean the same thing. Diagnostics are structured. The
          graph is queryable. Targets across languages share one declaration
          model. The result is a substrate that gets out of a developer's way
          and gives an agent something to reason about.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="fabrik-section" data-tone="muted">
  <div class="fabrik-container">
    <header class="fabrik-section-header">
      <span data-part="eyebrow">What Fabrik runs</span>
      <h2 data-part="title">One graph for every kind of work.</h2>
      <p data-part="lede">
        Languages with first-class targets, custom commands, and a cooperative path for existing toolchains all share the same content-addressed graph.
      </p>
    </header>

    {% set languages = [
      {
        name: "Rust",
        mark: "rust",
        body: "Per-crate targets for binaries, libraries, tests, and proc macros. Dependency resolution, compilation, and tests, all cached.",
        tags: ["Resolve", "Build", "Test"]
      },
      {
        name: "Swift",
        mark: "swift",
        body: "Apple platform targets for iOS and macOS, including simulator-aware runtimes for agents to launch, log, and inspect apps.",
        tags: ["Resolve", "Build", "Test"]
      },
      {
        name: "Elixir",
        mark: "elixir",
        body: "First-class Elixir and Erlang on a pinned OTP pair. Mix-free per-module compilation under one cached graph.",
        tags: ["Resolve", "Build", "Test"]
      }
    ] %}

    <div class="fabrik-grid" data-columns="4">
      {% for lang in languages %}
        <article class="fabrik-card" data-variant="language">
          <span data-part="mark">{{ langMark(lang.mark, 40) }}</span>
          <h3 data-part="title">{{ lang.name }}</h3>
          <p data-part="body">{{ lang.body }}</p>
          <ul data-part="tags">
            {% for tag in lang.tags %}
              <li>{{ tag }}</li>
            {% endfor %}
          </ul>
        </article>
      {% endfor %}
      <a class="fabrik-card" data-variant="language" data-ghost href="{{ site.github }}" rel="noopener">
        <span data-part="mark">{{ icon("plus") }}</span>
        <h3 data-part="title">Add a language</h3>
        <p data-part="body">The target model is open. Propose or contribute a new language frontend on GitHub.</p>
        <span data-part="cta">Contribute on GitHub &rarr;</span>
      </a>
    </div>

    {% set extras = [
      {
        title: "Tasks",
        body: "Any shell command becomes a content-addressed target. Declare argv, inputs, outputs, env, and resource needs; replays are cache hits.",
        icon: "terminal"
      },
      {
        title: "The cooperative model",
        body: "Fabrik coexists with your existing native toolchain configuration, cached as one action. Move to granular targets at your own pace. No rewrite to start.",
        icon: "plug"
      }
    ] %}

    <div class="fabrik-grid" data-columns="2">
      {% for ex in extras %}
        <article class="fabrik-card">
          <span data-part="icon">{{ icon(ex.icon) }}</span>
          <h3 data-part="title">{{ ex.title }}</h3>
          <p data-part="body">{{ ex.body }}</p>
        </article>
      {% endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="fabrik-section">
  <div class="fabrik-container">
    <div class="fabrik-split">
      <div>
        <span data-part="eyebrow">How it works</span>
        <h2 data-part="title">Declare targets, build the graph.</h2>
        <p data-part="lede">
          A fabrik.toml file declares targets in plain, structured form. Fabrik
          turns them into a content-addressed action graph that both humans and
          agents can inspect.
        </p>
        <ul data-part="bullets">
          <li>
            {{ icon("check") }}
            <span>Per-package <code>fabrik.toml</code>, one per directory.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            {{ icon("check") }}
            <span>Cache lives in <code>.fabrik/</code> at the workspace root. Gitignored.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            {{ icon("check") }}
            <span>A one-line edit in a leaf crate invalidates only that crate and its reverse deps.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fabrik-terminal">
        <div data-part="header">
          <span data-part="dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></span>
          <span data-part="title">app/fabrik.toml</span>
        </div>
        <pre data-part="body"><span data-part="muted">[[rust.library]]</span>
name = <span data-part="value">"greeter"</span>
srcs = [<span data-part="value">"src/lib.rs"</span>]

<span data-part="muted">[[rust.binary]]</span>
name = <span data-part="value">"hello"</span>
srcs = [<span data-part="value">"src/main.rs"</span>]
deps = [<span data-part="value">"greeter"</span>]

<span data-part="muted">[[rust.test]]</span>
name = <span data-part="value">"greeter_test"</span>
srcs = [<span data-part="value">"tests/greeter.rs"</span>]
crate_root = <span data-part="value">"tests/greeter.rs"</span>
deps = [<span data-part="value">"greeter"</span>]</pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="fabrik-section">
  <div class="fabrik-container">
    <header class="fabrik-section-header">
      <span data-part="eyebrow">FAQ</span>
      <h2 data-part="title">Questions, answered.</h2>
    </header>

    {% set faqs = [
      { q: "Is Fabrik production-ready?", a: "Fabrik builds Fabrik. The cargo_binary cooperative path is the production route today; granular targets are wiring up build-script support and per-target feature resolution." },
      { q: "Does it replace your native toolchain?", a: "No. You can run your native toolchain configuration in the cooperative model as a cached action, or use granular per-language targets where they exist. Most teams start cooperative and migrate to granular incrementally." },
      { q: "Why is this agent-native?", a: "Agents get the same APIs humans get: structured diagnostics, causality queries, and inspectable cache. The build is no longer a black box for the tool writing your code." },
      { q: "How is caching different?", a: "Every action is keyed by a content-addressed digest of its inputs and environment. The same digest hits locally, in CI, or on a remote build farm." }
    ] %}

    <div class="fabrik-faq">
      {% for faq in faqs %}
        <details>
          <summary>
            <span>{{ faq.q }}</span>
            <span data-part="icon">{{ icon("plus") }}</span>
          </summary>
          <p data-part="answer">{{ faq.a }}</p>
        </details>
      {% endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

